\textbf{Mr Tan harvested some cucumbers from his farm. He placed \(\frac{3}{4}\) kg of cucumbers equally into 5 baskets.} 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[\textbf{(a)}] \text{How many kilograms of cucumbers did he put in each basket?}
    \item[\textbf{(b)}] \text{Later, he collected another 2\(\frac{1}{2}\) kg of cucumbers and added it to the total amount he harvested earlier. What is the total mass of cucumbers he has now?}
\end{enumerate}

response_dict.solution:
\textbf{Solution}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[\textbf{(a)}] To find out how many kilograms of cucumbers Mr Tan put in each basket, divide \(\frac{3}{4}\) kg by 5:

    \[
    \frac{3}{4} \div 5 = \frac{3}{4} \times \frac{1}{5} = \frac{3}{20}
    \]

    So, each basket contains \(\frac{3}{20}\) kg of cucumbers.

    \item[\textbf{(b)}] The total mass of cucumbers originally is \(\frac{3}{4}\) kg.

    He adds another 2\(\frac{1}{2}\) kg. First, convert 2\(\frac{1}{2}\) kg to an improper fraction:
    \[
    2\frac{1}{2} = \frac{5}{2}
    \]

    Add \(\frac{3}{4}\) kg and \(\frac{5}{2}\) kg. Use common denominators:
    \[
    \frac{5}{2} = \frac{10}{4}
    \]
    So,
    \[
    \frac{3}{4} + \frac{10}{4} = \frac{13}{4} = 3\frac{1}{4}
    \]

    \textbf{Answer:}

    (a) \(\frac{3}{20}\) kg in each basket. 

    (b) Mr Tan has a total of \(3\frac{1}{4}\) kg of cucumbers now.
\end{enumerate}

